Gombe State Commissioner for Health, Ahmed Gana, yesterday, disclosed that seven suspected cases of Lassa Fever have been detected in the state. According to him, out of the seven suspected cases, two were confirmed, while the laboratory confirmation of the remaining five was being awaited. Among these, he said, two have died. The commissioner made the disclosure, while briefing newsmen in his Gombe office. He said one of the two that died was confirmed to have died of Lassa Fever, while confirmation on the cause of the second person’s death is still being awaited. “On the 6th of January, the first confirmed case was an indigine of Ibbi Local Government Area of Taraba State, and presented at the Federal Teaching Hospital Gombe, where he was diagnosed. He was treated accordingly and discharged home on the 16th of January. “The second case was brought unconscious from Bayo Local Government Area of Borno State, and was admitted into the Isolation Ward of the Teaching Hospital on the 23rd of January 2020, where he died on the same day. As at this morning, 4 patients are in the Isolation Ward” Gana added. He further told newsmen that his ministry, in line with national guidelines, activated its public health emergency operation centre for active surveillance across the entire state. Gana noted that parenteral and oral rivabirin, had been procured and distributed to strategic health facilities in the state. “There is ongoing capacity  building of all state health workers and sensitisation of the public through the media, the traditional and religious institution. The IEC materials have also been printed in Hausa and English languages, and have been distributed to public institutions” the commissioner stressed.